01-Simple models

Francisco E. Fonturbel

09/mar/2022

Anthropogenic effects on chungungos abundance

Here we will explore some anthropogenic variables as potential drivers of abundance change on this species

Lets do some nice ggplots to examine our data before fitting fancy models:

Uhhmm there is a trend in the two inferior panels, but error are too big.

Models

To do this, we will use a Poisson GLMM, using site and sampling month as random factors.

## lmerModLmerTest]

Well, it seems that none of our predictor variables are significant Also, R warns us that we have singular fit (this article to solve that)

Lets try some multi-model inference to examine the relative support of each variable to our dataset

Well, it seems that all predictor variables have similar importance.

Following Ben Bolkers advice, we can avoid singular fit by removing those random effects with a very litle contribution (in this case, month). Lets try fitting a new model using only site as random effect:

## Linear mixed model fit by REML. t-tests use Satterthwaite's method [
## lmerModLmerTest]
## Formula: abund ~ people + boats + pets + algae + (1 | site)
## 
## REML criterion at convergence: 220.4
## 
## Scaled residuals:

Well, there is no singular fit now, BUT none of our predictor variables is significant (doh!)

A Bayesian approach

As we have a relatively small (N = 34) sample size, well try now a Bayesian approach (based on Dimas code) to test the same but under a Bayesian framework based on Monte Carlo Markov Chains

## 
##  Iterations = 3001:12991
##  Thinning interval  = 10
##  Sample size  = 1000 
## 
##  DIC: 212.051 
## 
##  G-structure:  ~site
## 
##      post.mean l-95% CI u-95% CI eff.samp
## site     2.073   0.2131    6.256     1000
## 
##  R-structure:  ~units
## 
##       post.mean l-95% CI u-95% CI eff.samp
## units     1.057   0.7123    1.419     1000
## 
##  Location effects: abund ~ people + boats + pets + algae 
## 
##             post.mean l-95% CI u-95% CI eff.samp pMCMC   
## (Intercept)   2.32527  1.07293  3.54154   1000.0 0.002 **
## people        0.01648 -0.06448  0.09467   1000.0 0.704   
## boats        -0.07135 -0.26662  0.17550   1000.0 0.544   
## pets         -0.02345 -0.31553  0.27928   1000.0 0.874   
## algae        -0.06484 -0.89519  0.61398    852.5 0.940   
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

OK, it seems that there is no effect at all, as both approaches showed consistent results.
